
--> Some common entities of HTML :

1) &gt;	-	greater than
2) &lt;	-	less than
3) &amp; -	ampersand symbol
4) &pound; -	pound symbol
5) &copy;  -    copy symbol
6) &trade; -	trademark symbol


-> An exclusive 'header' element has been added to html5, seeing the frequent use of <div id = "header"> in html pages.

-> 'Pre' element shows text as is it is with carriage, spaces and tabs. These are useful for showing some code on web pages.


-> Blockquote tag is used to give the quotes.

-> Cite tag is used for citation.

-> Cite can be used as an attribute of blockquote tag.


->Embedded Style Sheet Syntax :

<style type="text/css">
p {
font-weight: bold;
color: red;
}
</style>





-> Anchor tag (<a>) has four classes or states : 

1. link
2. visited
3. hover
4. active






-> Rules and properties are applied according to specificity. That is which property related to an element is more specific for that element contents.





-> We can change the size, create padding and move a block-level element. 

-> For changing the width of the block we can name the block element as selector and 
   width: value
   height: value
   in the curly braces.

-> We can also give borders to block-level elements. Through CSS properties we can achieve various effects of borders namely:
   1) Border-style
   2) Border-width 
   3) Border-color

-> Types of borders :
 
- solid
- double
- inset
- ridge
- dashed
- dotted
- outset
- groove


-> Border-size can be given in pixels, points or ems
   Also border-size can be given as - thin, medium, thick.

	Border-top and Border-bottom are also 2 properties.


-> Padding and Margin are also CSS properties for block level elements.

-> To remove cell-spacing between the cells in borders the attribute is :

[ border-collapse: collapse; ]





-> Various layouts of CSS?????



-> Using CSS border and padding props for making links appear as buttons.

-> Using props to increase the link area.

-> Setting list items in horizontal line.




Various CSS Layout :-
------------------

1) Absolute :

position: absolute;
top: value;
left: value;

(relative to the container)



2) Relative :

position: relative;
top: value;
left: value;

(relative to previous position)



3) Float :

float: right or left or top or bottom;

(rest of the elements sets accordingly)




