							** HTML 5 **
							   ------



1. Abbreviation
   ------------

-> Markup an abbreviation, a shortened form of word or phrase.

Tag	-	<abbr>

E.g.	-	<p> This website is about <abbr title="Hyper Text Markup Language">HTML</abbr> and <abbr title="cascading style sheet">			CSS</abbr>. </p>




2. Quotation
   ---------

2.a) <q>	-	shorter quotation. 
2.b) <blockquote cite="www.wikipedia.org">	-	multi-line quotation

E.g.	-
<p>So I asked Bob about quotations on the Web and he said <q>I know as much about quotations as I do about pigeon fancying</q>.
Luckily, I found HTML Dog and it said:</p>

<blockquote cite="http://www.htmldog.com/guides/html/intermediate/text/">
    <p>blockquote and q are used for quotations. blockquote is generally used for standalone often multi-line quotations 
       whereas q is used for shorter, in-line quotations.</p>
</blockquote>



3. Citation
   --------

<cite>The cite </cite>



4. CODE
   ----

-> Represent any form of computer code.


5. VAR
   ---

-> Used for variables ( which could be a variable in anything, not just the code - it could be a variable in equation, for example)
 
<samp>	-	Sample OUTPUT
<kbd>	-	User Input (Keyboard)


E.g.-
----

<p>If you add the line <code><var>givevaderachuckle</var> = true;</code> to the <code>destroy_planet</code> subroutine and then type <kbd>ilovejabba</kbd> into the console, the big bad green Death Star laser will etch <samp>Slug Lover!</samp> on the planet's surface.</p>



6. PRE-FORMATTED TEXT
   ------------------

-> It takes notice of every every character in it, including whitespaces. Useful in places where indentation is relevant.

Tag	-	<pre>		</pre>

E.g.	-	

<pre><code>
&lt;div id="intro"&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;Some heading&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Some paragraph paragraph thing thing thingy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
</code></pre>







7. META TAGS
   ---------

-> Meta tags dont alter the appearance of the page, but is used by likes of search engine to catalogue information about the web page.

ATTRIBUTES :	name, http-equiv, content & CHARSET

-> "Content" is used in conjunction with "name" & "http-equiv" attributes


 a) NAME :	Its value can be anything you like. Common values are	-	"author", "description" & "keywords" 

 "author" is explicitly used to state one of the HTML page's authors
 "description" is often used by search engines to display a description of the web pages in the search results.



 b) HTTP-EQUIVALENT :	It will make an HTTP header, i.e. information sent to the server where the web page is held.
			This attribute is rarely used, but the possible values are:
  
   			"content-type"	-	encoding declaration
			"default-style"	-	Preferred style-sheet from a list of "link" and "style" elements.
			"refresh"	-	how often(in seconds) the page automatically refreshes or automatically redirects to
						another page. (considered a bad option for accessibility)



-> NOTE: (<meta charset = "UTF-8"/> is same as <meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html" charset="UTF-8"/>



E.g. -
---


<head>
    <title>Air conditioners? YEAH conditioners!</title>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <meta http-equiv="refresh" content="3"><!--not recommended for sane people-->
    <meta name="description" content="This is my really, really, REALLY exciting web page about air conditioners">
</head>


-> Also, <meta scheme="">, where "scheme" attribute defines how the value of the "content" attribute is interpreted.












8. ADDRESS
   -------

-> Used specifically for contact details, for the whole website or any article on a web-page.

TAG	-	<address>.....</address>



9. DEFINITION TERMS
   ----------------

TAG	-	<dfn title="">......</dfn>

-> Used to highlight 1st use of a term, and can be used to describe the term.

E.g.	-
---

<p>Bob's <dfn title="Dog">canine</dfn> mother and <dfn title="Horse">equine</dfn> father sat him down and carefully explained that he was an <dfn title="A mutation that combines two or more sets of chromosomes from different species">allopolyploid</dfn> organism.</p>





10. BI-DIRECTIONAL TEXT
    -------------------

-> It is used to reverse the direction of the text, and can be used to display the languages that read right-to-left.

TAG	-	<bdo dir="ltr" or "rtl"> ..... </bdo>	
 		
		"rtl" : right-to-left		"ltr" : left-to-right





11. EDITORIAL
    ---------

Two tags come under editorial	-	<del> & <ins>

-> They aren't limited to text and can be used over whole swathes of contents.


ATTRIBUTES:

 1) "datetime = "2014-01-26" " 	-	specifies when change was made.
 2) "cite = "http://www.xyz.com" "	-	specifies the reason for making the change.


E.g. -
----

<p>I have decided to <del datetime="2013-01-26">decrease</del> <ins cite="http://www.icecreamforall.com/changeofpolicy/">increase</ins> the amount of free ice cream that the State will provide for its citizens.</p>


-> By default, <del> is "STRIKE-THROUGH"	and 	<ins> is "UNDERLINE"





12. ARTICLES & SECTIONS
    -------------------

-> Article marksup the standalone section of the content. It can enclose 1 or more "general section tags".

<article>
    <section id="intro">
        <p>[An introduction]</p>
    </section>
    <section id="main_content">
        <p>[Content]</p>
    </section>
    <section id="related">
        <ul>
            <li><a href="that.html">That related article</a></li>
            <li><a href="this.html">This related article</a></li>
        </ul>
    </section>
</article>






13. HEADER & FOOTER
    ---------------

<body>
<article>
    <header>
        <h1>Alternatively&hellip;</h1>
        <p>[An introduction]</p>
    </header>
    <section id="main_content">
        <p>[Content]</p>
    </section>
    <footer>
        <p>[End notes]</p>
    </footer>
</article>
<footer>
    <p>[Copyright bumf]</p>
</footer>
</body>




